A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage is not consummated due to the incapacity of the respondent (Section 12(1)(a) HMA); 
2. if the respondent has consented to the marriage under duress or undue influence (Section 12(1)(c) HMA); 
3. if the respondent was suffering from mental disorder, mental incapacity, or recurring attacks of insanity or epilepsy at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA); 
4. if the respondent has been suffering from a venereal disease in a communicable form at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(e) HMA); 
5. if the respondent has been pregnant by some other person other than the petitioner at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(f) HMA); 
6. if the consent of the petitioner or the guardian was obtained by fraud or force (Section 12(1)(d) and (g) HMA); 
7. if the respondent is not of sound mind or is suffering from a mental disorder at the time of filing the petition (Section 12(1)(h) and (i) HMA, as added by the Marriage Laws (Amendment) Act, 1976).

